{"source_key":"sha256-46306f7e5fd51cf460ea5434a8fefe6f","record_index":1596,"record_hash":"sha256:aa2455da5c5d50776aec8dfa61093b5e775cf0d00fde05ee18d6c0c8f5244b2e","timestamp":"2026-06-09T12:11:32.703Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"{\"previous_status\":{\"completed\":\"Findings:\\n\\n- **[P2] 15-minute cap is not actually global.** [skill.rs]([REDACTED:path]) lets a changed fingerprint bypass the debounce, so `missing` then `outdated:version` can show twice inside 15 minutes. That conflicts with “at most every 15 mins.” Simpler: timestamp gate first; fingerprint can still be stored, but it shouldn’t bypass the 15-minute wall.\\n\\n- **[P2] Debounce suppresses output, not the check cost.** [skill.rs]([REDACTED:path]) runs `check_skill_status(...)` before looking at debounce state. So every agent mutation still does the skill check even when we know we won’t show the notice. If perf is part of the goal, read the cache first and return `None` when the last notice was under 15 minutes ago.\\n\\nNo other important issues from the quick pass. The DB state shape is fine, and I don’t see skill-check failures leaking into command failure.\"}}","tool_name":"close_agent","tool_kind":"housekeeping","tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-06-09T12:11:32.703Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}